<div id="other-internet-resources">

<h2 id="Oth">Other Internet Resources</h2>

<ul>

<li>Kilcullen, John, and Jon Robinson, &ldquo;Medieval Political Philosophy&rdquo;,
 <em>Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy</em> (Winter 2024 Edition),
Edward N. Zalta &amp; Uri Nodelman (eds.), URL =
 &lt;<a href="https://plato.stanford.edu/archives/win2024/entries/medieval-political/">https://plato.stanford.edu/archives/win2024/entries/medieval-political/</a>&gt;.
 [This was the previous entry on this topic in the <em>Stanford
Encyclopedia of Philosophy</em> &ndash; see the
<a href="https://plato.stanford.edu/cgi-bin/encyclopedia/archinfo.cgi?entry=medieval-political" class="plain" target="other">version history</a>.]</li>


<li>Bible

<ul>

 <li><a href="https://www.drbo.org/" target="other">Douai-Rheims Bible</a></li>
 
 <li><a href="https://www.vatican.va/archive/bible/nova_vulgata/documents/nova-vulgata_index_lt.html" target="other"><em>Nova Vulgata</em></a>,
 Latin text of the Vulgate Bible.</li>
</ul> </li>

<li>Quran

<ul>

 <li><a href="https://guides.lib.uw.edu/research/quran" target="other">Quran in different English translations</a>,
 Translations and Searchable versions of the Quran. List maintained by
the University of Washington Libraries.</li>
</ul> </li>

<li>Tanach

<ul>

 <li><a href="https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/the-tanakh-full-text" target="other">Torah, Navi, Ketuvim</a>
 in English translations, Jewish Virtual library.</li>
</ul> </li>

<li>Texts and Translations (Christian)

<ul>

 <li><a href="https://www.newadvent.org/fathers/" target="other">New Advent: Fathers of the Church</a>,
 includes translations of the main works of Augustine
 (<a href="https://www.newadvent.org/fathers/1201.htm" target="other"><em>The City of God</em></a>,
 <a href="https://www.newadvent.org/fathers/1101.htm" target="other"><em>Confessions</em></a> etc.), Thomas Aquinas&rsquo;
 <a href="https://www.newadvent.org/summa/" target="other"><em>Summa Theologiae</em></a>
 and other works of the Church Fathers.</li>

 <li><a href="https://www.ccel.org/" target="other">Christian Classics Ethereal Library</a>,
 includes many texts in translation, including the
 <a href="https://www.ccel.org/fathers.html" target="other">Early Church Fathers</a>.</li>
 
<li>Thomas Aquinas. His writings are available at the
 <a href="https://www.corpusthomisticum.org/" target="other"><em>Corpus Thomisticum</em></a>,
 the fundamental website for the study of Aquinas.</li>

<li>Peter of Auvergne, archive of
 <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20210227025834/http:/www.paleography.unifr.ch/petrus_de_alvernia/" target="other">Petrus de Alvernia site</a>
 at the University of Freiburg, devoted to the life and works of Peter
of Auvergne (archived on the Internet Archive).</li>
</ul> </li>

<li>Texts and Translations (Muslim)

<ul>

 <li><a href="https://sourcebooks.fordham.edu/islam/islamsbook.asp" target="other">Internet Islamic History Sourcebook</a>,
 Paul Halsall (ed.), includes many online primary sources (including
online texts by Islamic philosophers and political writers) and
fundamental texts on the history of Islam.</li>

 <li><a href="https://muslimphilosophy.org/" target="other">Islamic Philosophy Online</a>,
 includes primary sources and bibliography on medieval Islamic
philosophy as well.</li>

<li>Al-F&#257;r&#257;b&#299;, some of his works are available at
 <a href="https://www.muslimphilosophy.com/farabi/" target="other">Muslim Philosophy</a>.</li>
 
<li>Ibn Rushd/Averroes,
 <a href="https://dare.uni-koeln.de/" target="other">Digital Averroes Research Environment (DARE)</a>
 A digital collection of editions, manuscripts, prints (by the Thomas
Institute of the University of Cologne).</li>

<li>Ibn Khald&#363;n,
 <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20110822074740/http:/www.muslimphilosophy.com/ik/Muqaddimah/index.htm" target="other">The Muqaddimah</a>,
 full online text, trans. by Franz Rosenthal. (archived on the
Internet Archive)</li>
</ul> </li>

<li>Texts and Translations (Jewish)

<ul>

 <li><a href="https://sourcebooks.fordham.edu/jewish/jewishsbook.asp" target="other">Internet Jewish History Sourcebook</a>,
 Paul Halsall (ed.), includes many online primary sources (including
online texts by some Jewish philosophers) and fundamental texts on the
history of Judaism.</li>

 <li><a href="https://lib.guides.umd.edu/c.php?g=326553&amp;p=2197255" target="other">Jewish sacred texts online</a>,
 Compiled by University of Maryland (some in English
translations).</li>

<li>Judah Ha-Levi,
 <a href="https://sourcebooks.fordham.edu/source/kuzari.asp" target="other">The Kuzari, (part I)</a>,
 translated by Hartwig Hirschfeld (1905). A philosophical treatise
written in the form of a dialogue between the king of the Khazars and
the representatives of various belief systems, including a rabbi.</li>

<li>Moses Maimonides,
 <a href="https://sacred-texts.com/jud/gfp/" target="other">The Guide for the Perplexed</a>,
 translated by M. Friedl&auml;nder (1903).</li>
</ul> </li>

<li>Texts and Translations of Significant Historical Texts from the
 <a href="https://sourcebooks.fordham.edu/sbook.asp" target="other">Internet Medieval Sourcebook</a>,
 Paul Halsall (ed.):

<ul>

 <li><a href="https://sourcebooks.fordham.edu/source/sunnah-horne.asp" target="other">The Sunnah</a>,
 Traditions of the Prophet Muhammad (tr. unattributed).</li>

 <li><a href="https://ballandalus.wordpress.com/2015/07/05/last-will-and-testament-of-imam-ali-ibn-abi-talib-d-661/" target="other">Ali ibn Abi Talib, the 4th Caliph, Last Will and Testament</a>
 (tr. Mohammed Ballan).</li>

 <li><a href="https://sourcebooks.fordham.edu/source/rambam13.asp" target="other">Moses Maimonides, The 13 Principles of Judaism</a>,
 (tr. unattributed).</li>

 <li><a href="https://sourcebooks.fordham.edu/source/B8-unam.asp" target="other">Boniface VIII, <em>Unam sanctam</em></a>
 (tr. unattributed).</li>

 <li><a href="https://sourcebooks.fordham.edu/source/donatconst.asp" target="other">The Donation of Constantine</a>
 (tr. Ernest F. Henderson).</li>
</ul> </li>

<li>Jonathan Robinson maintains some translations of medieval texts
which pertain to medieval political thought and the Franciscan poverty
controversy on
 <a href="http://individual.utoronto.ca/jwrobinson/#Translations" target="other">Robinson&rsquo;s website</a>.</li>
 
<li>Resources relating to Islamic and Jewish jurisprudence:

<ul>

 <li><a href="https://sourcebooks.fordham.edu/source/misc-hadith.asp" target="other">Islamic Hadith, short excerpts</a>.</li>
 
<li>Arthur Jeffry (ed.),
 <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20010417223754/http:/ccat.sas.upenn.edu/~rs143/Resources/ajwiba.html" target="other">A Reader on Islam</a>:
 Passages from Standard Arabic Writings Illustrative of the Beliefs
and Practices of Muslims. (archived on the Internet Archive)</li>

<li>Joseph Schact:
 &ldquo;<a href="https://sourcebooks.fordham.edu/med/schacht.asp" target="other">Law and Justice</a>&rdquo;,
 in <em>Cambridge Encyclopaedia of Islam</em>, vol. II, pt. VIII/chap.
4.</li>

<li>Moses Maimonides,
 <a href="https://sourcebooks.fordham.edu/source/rambam-yesodei-hatorah.txt" target="other">The Law and Basic Principles of the Torah</a>
 (tr. Immanuel M. O&rsquo; Levy).</li>

<li>A translation of the
 <a href="https://torah.org/series/shulchan-aruch/" target="other">Shulchan Aruch and Mishna Berurah</a>.
 Code of Jewish Law and a commentary by Rabbi Yisrael Meir Kagan of
<em>Orach Chayim</em>, the first part of the <em>Shulchan
Aruch</em>.</li>
</ul> </li>
</ul>
</div>

